                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> This is the duplicate I gave him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> This book was pawned by a young <hi rend="italic">chap</hi>, at Mr. Blackburn's, in Skinner-street, Somers-town, on the 27th of Feb., being in the trade (a plasterer,) I thought it would be useful to me, and bought the ticket of him and redeemed it the same day; I took it to Mr. Gill's; had I known it was stolen I should not have kept the ticket.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450407-name-930" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-930" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-930" type="surname" value="BLACKBURN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450407-name-930" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES BLACKBURN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am assistant to my father, who is a pawn<lb></lb>broker. I was applied to to search our books—I looked at the dates of 26th and 27th of Feb., and found no book of this kind pledged on those days—only one book was pledged, and that was a Bible which we have now.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> I did not take the book or anything else out of the prose<lb></lb>cutor's place; if I had stolen it I should not have pawned it where I was well known.</p>
